SIMPLE: material
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Material
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>materialis</ets>, fr. <ets>materia</ets> stuff, matter: cf. F.
<ets>mat⟦eacute⟧riel</ets>. See <er>Matter</er>, and cf.
<er>Mat⟦eacute⟧riel</er>.]</ety> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of matter; not spiritual; corporeal;
physical; <as>as, <ex>material</ex> substance or bodies</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>material</qex> elements of the universe.</q>
<rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Pertaining to, or affecting,
the physical nature of man, as distinguished from the
<contr>mental</contr> or <contr>moral</contr> nature; relating to the
bodily wants, interests, and comforts; <as>as, <ex>material</ex>
well-being; <ex>material</ex> comforts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of solid or weighty character; not insubstantial; of
consequence; not be dispensed with; important; significant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Discourse, which was always <qex>material</qex>, never
trifling.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall, in the account of simple ideas, set down only such as are
most <qex>material</qex> to our present purpose.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Logic.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the matter, as
opposed to the form, of a thing. See <er>Matter</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Material cause</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Cause</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Material evidence</b></col>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>evidence which conduces to the proof or disproof
of a relevant hypothesis.</cd> <au>Wharton.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Corporeal; bodily; important; weighty; momentous;
essential.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Material</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Material
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The substance or matter of
which anything is made or may be made.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Raw material</b></col>, <cd>any crude, unfinished, or
elementary materials that are adapted to use only by processes of
skilled labor. <as>Cotton, wool, ore, logs, etc., are <ex>raw
material</ex></as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Material</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Material
<hw>Ma*te"ri*al</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To form from matter; to
materialize.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Materialism</ent>⟦br⟧
